We first identify the cash and cash equivalents on the balance sheet. In this case, these are given as:

• Cash on Hand (End): 2,103,508.95  
• Bank Deposits (End): 4,714,000.00  

So the total cash and cash equivalents = 2,103,508.95 + 4,714,000.00 = 6,817,508.95

Next, the total current liabilities are given by the sum of the current liabilities accounts. Here:

• Accounts Payable (End): 302,000.00  
• Taxes Payable (End): 197,821.72  

Thus the Total Current Liabilities = 302,000.00 + 197,821.72 = 499,821.72

Finally, the Cash to Current Debt Ratio is calculated by dividing Total Cash and Cash Equivalents by Total Current Liabilities:

  Cash to Current Debt Ratio = 6,817,508.95 / 499,821.72 ≈ 13.63

So, the solution is:
